For any distributive lattice D, \operatorname {Spec} D is spectral. This gives us a functor
 \operatorname {Spec} : \mathbf {DL}^{\mathrm {op}} \to  \mathbf {Spec} 
from distributive lattices to spectral spaces.

If we now start from a closed set Y, for any x\in X we have
 egin {align*} x\in C_{\mathcal {I}_Y} &\Leftrightarrow 1 
ot \in \mathcal {I}_{Y,x} \ &\Leftrightarrow  orall U	ext {open}
i x.\, 1 
ot \in \mathcal {I}_Y(U) \ &\Leftrightarrow  orall U	ext {open}
i x.\, Y \cap U 
eq \emptyset \ &\Leftrightarrow x \in Y \end {align*}
The third equivalence holds since by construction, 1 \in \mathcal {I}_Y(U) \Leftrightarrow  orall y \in Y \cap U.\ y 
ot \models 1 \Leftrightarrow Y \cap U = \emptyset . The final equivalence holds since Y is closed.

  A map of locally distributed spaces f : X \to  Y is a quasi-closed immersion if 

f is a homeomorphism of X onto a closed subspace of Y;  

f_{\sharp } : \mathcal {O}_{Y} \twoheadrightarrow  f_*\mathcal {O}_{X} \cong  \mathcal {I}/\mathcal {O}_{Y} for some sheaf of ideals \mathcal {I} of \mathcal {O}_{Y}.

Let X be a locally distributed space, and \mathcal {I} a sheaf of ideal of \mathcal {O}_{X}. We define the subset of X
 C_{\mathcal {I}} := \{x \in  X\mid 1 \not \in  \mathcal {I}_x\} 
Equivalently, x\in  C_{\mathcal {I}} iff the stalk (\mathcal {I}/\mathcal {O}_{X})_x of the quotient distributive lattice at x is non-trivial. This is a closed set, since if 0 = 1 inÂ (\mathcal {I}/\mathcal {O}_{X})_x, then 0=1 in an open neighbourhood of x.

Consider the affine scheme \operatorname {Spec} 2[x] mentioned in Example . Note that sheaf on \operatorname {Spec} 2[x] are simply presheaves on the Sierpinski space 2 = \{0 < 1\}. Hence, we have a sheaf of ideal \mathcal {I} of \mathcal {O}_{2[x]} as follows, which corresponds to
\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver} \begin {tikzcd} {\mathcal I(\{0,1\}) = 0 \cong \mathcal I_0} & {2[x]} \\ {\mathcal I(\{1\}) = 2 \cong \mathcal I_1} & 2 \arrow [tail, from=1-1, to=1-2] \arrow [tail, from=1-1, to=2-1] \arrow ["{x=1}", from=1-2, to=2-2] \arrow [from=2-1, to=2-2] \end {tikzcd}
According to Construction , the closed subspace is given by C_{\mathcal {I}} = \{0\}, where the structural sheaf given by \mathcal {O}_{C_{\mathcal {I}},0} \cong 0/2[x] \cong 2[x]. This way, we get a quasi-closed immersion C_{\mathcal {I}} \hookrightarrow \operatorname {Spec} 2[x], where now C_{\mathcal {I}} is not a scheme.

Let X be a scheme, and \mathcal {I} an ideal of \mathcal {O}_{X}. \mathcal {I} is quasi-coherent iff for all affine open \operatorname {Spec} A of X and a\in  A, the canonical factorisation

\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
  \begin {tikzcd}
    {\mathcal  I(\mathrm {Spec} A)} \\
    {a \wedge  \mathcal  I(\mathrm {Spec}A)} & {\mathcal  I(\mathrm {Spec}A/a)}
    \arrow [two heads, from=1-1, to=2-1]
    \arrow [from=1-1, to=2-2]
    \arrow [from=2-1, to=2-2]
  \end {tikzcd}


induces an equivalence a \wedge  \mathcal {I}(\operatorname {Spec} A) = \mathcal {I}(\operatorname {Spec} A/a).

If we now start from a closed set Y, for any x\in X we have
 egin {align*} x\in C_{\mathcal {I}_Y} &\Leftrightarrow 1 
ot \in \mathcal {I}_{Y,x} \ &\Leftrightarrow  orall U	ext {open}
i x.\, 1 
ot \in \mathcal {I}_Y(U) \ &\Leftrightarrow  orall U	ext {open}
i x.\, Y \cap U 
eq \emptyset \ &\Leftrightarrow x \in Y \end {align*}
The third equivalence holds since by construction, 1 \in \mathcal {I}_Y(U) \Leftrightarrow  orall y \in Y \cap U.\ y 
ot \models 1 \Leftrightarrow Y \cap U = \emptyset . The final equivalence holds since Y is closed.

