  By the sheaf condition, \mathcal {O}_{D}(I) is the following equaliser,

  \usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
    \begin {tikzcd}
      \mathcal  O_{D}(I) \ar [r, tail] & \prod _{p\in  I} D/p \ar [r, shift left] \ar [r, shift right] & \prod _{p,q\in  I} D/p\wedge  q
    \end {tikzcd}


  Hence, an element u\in \mathcal {O}_{D}(I) is exactly a function u : I \to  D such that

u(i) \le  i for all i\in  I;

u(i) \wedge  j = u(i \wedge  j) for all i,j\in  I.
  This gives an I-element, since for any a\in  D,
   u(i \wedge  a) = u(i \wedge  i \wedge  a) = u(i) \wedge  i \wedge  a = u(i) \wedge  a. 
  On the other hand, it suffices to show an I-element is always contractive. But this is easy, since
   u(i) = u(i \wedge  i) = u(i) \wedge  i. 
  Hence, \mathcal {O}_{D}(I) is the set of all I-elements of D.

