Let \mathbb {H}[x] be the free Heyting algebra with one generator. The spectrum \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x] as a topological space is the Rieger-Nishimura laddar,
\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver} \begin {tikzcd} \bullet && \bullet \\ \bullet && \bullet \\ \bullet && \bullet \\ \bullet && \bullet \\ \vdots && \vdots \\ & \bullet \arrow [from=2-1, to=1-1] \arrow [from=2-1, to=1-3] \arrow [from=2-3, to=1-3] \arrow [from=3-1, to=2-1] \arrow [from=3-1, to=2-3] \arrow [from=3-3, to=1-1] \arrow [from=3-3, to=2-3] \arrow [from=4-1, to=3-1] \arrow [from=4-1, to=3-3] \arrow [from=4-3, to=2-1] \arrow [from=4-3, to=3-3] \arrow [from=5-1, to=4-1] \arrow [from=5-1, to=4-3] \arrow [from=5-3, to=3-1] \arrow [from=5-3, to=4-3] \arrow [from=6-2, to=5-1] \arrow [from=6-2, to=5-3] \end {tikzcd}
It has a unique non-standard open subscheme, which we denote as \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]_+ = \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]-\{\bot \}, where \bot is the generic point of \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]. The open subscheme \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x] is not compact, hence it is not affine.
